# ğŸ“ Linux File Permissions â€” Numeric Mode (`chmod`)

## ğŸ” What Are File Permissions in Linux?

Every file in Linux has three types of users:
- ğŸ‘¤ **Owner** (user who created the file)
- ğŸ‘¥ **Group** (users in the same group)
- ğŸŒ **Others** (everyone else)

And three types of access:
- `r` â†’ Read
- `w` â†’ Write
- `x` â†’ Execute

---

## ğŸ”¢ Numeric (Octal) Permission System

Permissions are represented by **numbers** (0â€“7), using this rule:

| Permission | Binary | Value |
|------------|--------|-------|
| Read (`r`) | 100    | 4     |
| Write (`w`)| 010    | 2     |
| Execute (`x`) | 001 | 1     |

Add the values to set permissions:

| Access | Binary | Value | Symbolic |
|--------|--------|--------|-----------|
| `rwx`  | 111    | 7      | full access |
| `rw-`  | 110    | 6      | read + write |
| `r--`  | 100    | 4      | read only |
| `r-x`  | 101    | 5      | read + execute |
| `--x`  | 001    | 1      | execute only |
| `---`  | 000    | 0      | no access |

---

## ğŸ§® Structure of `chmod XYZ file`

- X = permission for **Owner**
- Y = permission for **Group**
- Z = permission for **Others**

Example:
```bash
chmod 755 script.sh

#####ğŸ¯ Common chmod Values
Value	Meaning	Symbolic
600 ---	Only owner can read/write	rw-------
644 ---	Owner rw, others read	rw-r--r--
700	--- Only owner can do everything	rwx------
755 ---	Everyone can read/execute, only owner can write	rwxr-xr-x
400 ---	Read-only for owner	r--------
777 ---	Everyone can do everything âš ï¸	rwxrwxrwx

### ğŸ± Linux `cat` Command â€” Functions & Usage

The `cat` (concatenate) command is used to read, create, append, and merge text files in Linux.

---

## ğŸ“„ Common `cat` Functions

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `cat file.txt` | Displays the contents of `file.txt` |
| `cat > file.txt` | Creates a new file and allows input (overwrites if exists); finish with `Ctrl + D` |
| `cat >> file.txt` | Appends text to the end of an existing file |
| `cat file1.txt file2.txt` | Displays contents of both files |
| `cat file1.txt file2.txt > file3.txt` | Merges file1 and file2 into a new file3 |
| `cat -n file.txt` | Shows file content with line numbers |
| `cat` | Accepts input from user and displays it (until `Ctrl + D`) |

---

## ğŸ§ª Example Practice

```bash
cat > hello.txt
# Type: Hello world!
# Press Ctrl + D

cat hello.txt
# Output: Hello world!

cat >> hello.txt
# Type: Adding more lines...
# Press Ctrl + D

cat hello.txt
# Output:
# Hello world!
# Adding more lines...

cat -n hello.txt
# Output:
#     1	Hello world!
#     2	Adding more lines...

## ğŸ” File Transfer between Laptop â†” EC2

### ğŸ”¹ Upload from Laptop â†’ EC2  (using **scp**)

```bash
scp -i "day9key.pem" day9.txt ec2-user@52.14.154.42:/home/ec2-user/
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
scp -- Secure Copy command (transfer files over SSH)
-i --	Tells scp which SSH private key to use
"day9key.pem" --	Private key file used for authentication
day9.txt --	File on my local laptop to send
ec2-user@52.14.154.42 -- 	Username (ec2-user) and Public IP of EC2 server
:/home/ec2-user/ --	Target folder inside EC2 where the file will be placed

